$ Python: input
@ input

`input()` reads a line from → development/stdin-stdout-stderr[stdin] and returns it:

The following example prompts the user to enter his/her name and password and assigns the values to two → development/languages/Python/variables[variables].
gh|about-Python|/built-in/functions/input/demo.py||

{ Reading passwords #py-input-password

  When using `input`, the value that the user enters is displayed on the console. This is not always desired, especially when entering → development/security/password[passwords].
  In order to hide the entered value, the function `getpass()`, found in the equally named → development/languages/Python/standard-library module → development/languages/Python/standard-library/getpass can be used:
  gh|about-Python|/built-in/functions/input/password.py||

}

